# Maze Search (Prolog)

## Overview
This project implements a maze solver and path validator in Prolog. It can:

- Generate random mazes (generate_maze.pl)
- Display them (display_map/1)
- Locate the start cell `s`
- Find a path to the exit `e` using DFS

## Files and Structure

| File | Description |
|------|-------------|
| vitalii_project_2.pl | Maze solver: find_start, path validation, DFS search, movement rules. |
| generate_maze.pl | Maze generator (gen_map/4) and map renderer (display_map/1). |
| README.md | This documentation. |


## Core Components

| Predicate | Purpose |
|-----------|---------|
| find_exit/2 | Main interface: generate path (DFS) or validate a supplied path. |
| find_start/2 | Locates the single start cell `s`. |
| valid_path/3 | Walks a move sequence and checks if it ends on `e`. |
| dfs/3 | Sets up the DFS and returns a path. |
| dfs_loop/4 | DFS engine; two goal clauses allow solution emission and continued search. |
| push_on_stack/4 | Builds new DFS frames. |
| move/3 | Defines directional moves. |
| check_wall/2 | Ensures next cell is not a wall. |
| walk/4 | Executes a move list from a given position. |


## Running the Program

Load everything:

    ?- [vitalii_project_2, test].
    ?- set_prolog_flag(answer_write_options, [max_depth(0)]).


## Usage

### Generate and Solve a Maze

    ?- gen_map(4, 15, 15, M),
       display_map(M),
       find_exit(M, A).

`A` is a move list leading from `s` to `e`.


    ?- basic_map(M),
       display_map(M),
       find_exit(M, [right, right, down]).

Succeeds only if the path is legal and ends on `e`.

